# packr — Core Rules

Modular image compression benchmarking library. Classical codecs (LZ4, TAR, JPEG) and ML codecs (ONNX autoencoders from `elemental`) behind a shared `Encoder`/`Decoder` interface. Config via Hydra. Uses `uv` for Python env.

## Import Convention
`src/` is on `PYTHONPATH`. Import as `from compression_engine.base import Encoder` — never `from src.compression_engine...`.

## Commands
```bash
uv sync --extra dev
uv run python src/runner.py                                      # default (lz4)
uv run python src/runner.py compression_engine=<engine>          # switch engine
uv run python src/runner.py benchmark=<bench_group>              # switch benchmarks
uv run pytest tests/
```

## Hydra Configs
All configs live in `config/` (singular). Entry point: `config/config.yaml`. Sub-configs in `config/compression_engine/` and `config/benchmark/` are composed via `defaults:`. Objects are instantiated with `_target_` through `hydra.utils.instantiate`.

## Encoder/Decoder Split
Every engine is a `CompressionEngine(encoder, decoder)`. Each side is independently instantiable (for future streaming). Encoded `bytes` must be self-describing — the decoder must reconstruct without shared state.

## Canonical Image Format
Internal format: **HWC uint8 RGB numpy**. Funnel all public inputs through `utils.image.ensure_array`. Don't branch on input type elsewhere.

## Benchmark Contract
Benchmarks are stateful callables. `__call__` computes per-image metrics and appends via `self._add_result(dict)`. `summarize()` reduces `self._results` to stats. Benchmarks that need the active engine expose `compression_engine = None`; the runner injects it via `Benchmarks.bind_engine`.

## Documentation
Every `src/` subdirectory has `README.md` (usage) and `ARCHITECTURE.md` (implementation).
**Update both for every directory you modify.** Also update outermost `README.md` if project-level docs change. Outdated docs are worse than no docs.

## Planning
If a task has more than 3 steps, create a plan first before executing.

## Testing
Tests mirror `src/` under `tests/`. ONNX tests auto-skip if `onnxruntime` or model files are missing — preserve this when adding ONNX-dependent tests. Add tests for new behavior only.
